I'm beginning to wonder if I'm going to have to bail out of this 30 day practice :\ I'm on the heavier side, and the last 3 days have had some stuff that has been pretty brutal on me. I couldn't do the side-to-side frog hop things on day 21 because that would have DESTROYED my knees, and I could just barely handle the supported one-arm planks yesterday. And now today flying from one side to the other with unsupported one-armed planks? As if that's a perfectly reasonable progression from supported ones? The other two days I could stand it because she at least offered an alternative, and acknowledged that might be too much for some. But today there was no acknowledgement of that, I was like "Okay...guess I'll just stay here in plank then..." Normally Adriene is really good at reasonable progressions and offering alternatives for those with different body types, but the last three days of this practice I'm just feeling more and more isolated.
Thank you ❤

Comment #2. This came to mind as I was browsing the comments (I LOVE reading comments. I saw someone else say this on another video, but your comment section is nothing but love and light).


With most workout or yoga videos I've done on youtube, I usually give up when it gets hard. I either quit the video all together or I sit out the pieces that I struggle with. This is problematic as it means that I teach myself not to ever push myself and that it takes me a long time to get stronger. So long, in fact, that I normally give up. I know there are some day when you need to take it easy (that's why it's taking me longer than 30 days to get through this) but I also know you do have to push yourself sometimes... so I started pushing myself through the hard parts back in the first week of videos.


From pushing myself I learned one amazing thing: to trust Adriene. I noticed that you really seem to know your audience well and you never throw out more than I can handle. Usually, when I give up, you only do one more or one more cycle of breath and I always end up thinking, "I totally could of made it through that" to the point where I find myself rarely giving up anymore. When I want to I think to myself, "Trust, she never does more than you can handle." And sometimes your mantra of, "You have everything you need here". I can definitely feel myself getting stronger, physically and mentally.

I forgot to write that in the Day 22 practice when we extended our legs out into plank I accidentally kicked my cat in the face and had to cease and desist yoga so that I could try to convince him that it was an accident and that I loved him very dearly.

:) I haven't been commenting as much because I feel as if I have less and less to say. I feel like my emotions and thoughts have calmed down... I am more steady... and today I was really able to embrace the JOY. I've been a lot kinder to myself. I'm not sure if it's the yoga or the yoga and a combination of other factors but I'm starting to feel happier.

It's my 6th year of yoga and I noticed during this challenge that I'm really not mindful about my feet. I also fractured my left foot 5 years ago, and some pain is still there. So being mindful of it often results in feeling like 'damn, that'll never be the same again'. I decided to take more notice anyhow, send more energy there, keep them engaged, feel the ground, the list goes on. I didn't notice any changes until today. I was snowboarding after a year off and oh my goodness, all that new awareness in my feet brought much more control and made me fly down the slopes! I couldn't even believe myself. I'm only now starting to understand the 'what you do on the mat shows in everyday life' concept. I'm so joyful, I had to share :)

This yoga journey has already opened me in ways I never imagined. Recently, I was asked for a class to write an 'ode to too familiar things'. Things that I take for granted. This is what I wrote. I think some of you might relate. 

I step on my yoga mat everyday,
to connect with myself,
to treasure myself, 
like old women worship
photos of their youth. 
As if their nubile bodies
were roman sculptures,
now worn by the wind 
and water of time. 

I find my feet on my mat. 
Heels and toes kissing the firm,
yet forgiving surface. 
Steady as an ancient forest, 
my mat cradles me. 
She is a dedicated mother,
supporting her newborn.

Here I am able to land. 
Setting aside the to-do lists,
the worries, 
this sense of ‘never enough’,
scattered like trash in my mind.

She protects me in this way.
Shielding me from the chaos,
allowing me to find sanctuary.
My breath surrenders to this temple
of clear skies and silent solace.
I dedicate myself to this sacred ocean of discovery,
and in return,
I am held by her, 
with the resolve of Buddhist monks seeking alms, 
and scrubbing the floors of their Stupa.

Here my mat plants seeds of trust 
into the garden of my soul. 
She nourishes me with 
The echo of my breath, 
the wisdom of my heart. 
She makes me whole.
